[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(26) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Forty thousand.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—By comparison with the parallel passage in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Chronicles 9:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and with the notice in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 10:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (one thousand four hundred), it seems clear that for “forty thousand” “four thousand” should be read. They were kept in various “chariot cities,” as well as at Jerusalem. This multiplication of horses and horsemen—forbidden to the future king in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but foretold by Samuel at the inauguration of the kingdom (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 8:11-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")—is significant of military conquest and an extended empire. The Israelite armies, in frequent contradistinction from their enemies, had been hitherto mainly of infantry; and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 11:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the chariots and horses captured were not used, but destroyed, “as the Lord bade Joshua.” Such armies were powerful for defence, not for invasion. Now, as it would seem for the first time, this provision of the ancient law, like many others, was set aside, and Solomon’s empire assumed the character of other great Oriental monarchies.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:26",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 4:26",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Solomon had forty thousand stalls of horses for chariots — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 9:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", it is said, he had but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "four thousand. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And Bochart thinks that the Hebrew word here used should be rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "four, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "forty, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or that some error has crept into the text in regard to the number here mentioned. It is justly observed, however, by Poole, that the Hebrew word translated ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "stalls ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "here, is not exactly the same word which is used, and so translated, in Chronicles; and that, therefore, there may well be allowed some difference in the signification; the one signifying, properly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "stables; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "of such there were four thousand; the other ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "stalls, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "partitions ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for each horse, which were forty thousand. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For his chariots — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Both for his military chariots, which seem to be those fourteen hundred, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and for divers other uses, as respecting his great and various buildings, and merchandises, and other occasions, which might require some thousands of other chariots. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And twelve thousand horsemen — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Appointed partly for the defence of his people in peace, and partly for attendance upon his person, and for the splendour of his government.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "4:20-28 Never did the crown of Israel shine so bright, as when Solomon wore it. He had peace on all sides. Herein, his kingdom was a type of the Messiah's; for to Him it is promised that he shall have the heathen for his inheritance, and that princes shall worship him. The spiritual peace, and joy, and holy security, of all the faithful subjects of the Lord Jesus, were typified by that of Israel. The kingdom of God is not, as Solomon's was, meat and drink, but, what is infinitely better, righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost. The vast number of his attendants, and the great resort to him, are shown by the provision daily made. Herein Christ far outdoes Solomon, that he feeds all his subjects, not with the bread that perishes, but with that which endures to eternal life.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 9:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the number of stalls for Solomon's chariot horses is stated at 4,000, instead of 40,000. The number in the present passage is probably a corruption. Solomon's chariots were but 1,400 ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for which 40,000 horses could not possibly be required. The Assyrian chariots had at most three horses apiece, while some had only two. 4,000 horses would supply the full team of three to 1,200, and the smaller team of two to 200 chariots. The number 4,000 is in due proportion to the 12,000 horses for cavalry, and is in accordance with all that we know of the military establishments of the time and country. Compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
